Cook - a couple of questions, if I may. I spent two years and three months incountry, in a line unit. Granted, there are differences in how an army unit and and a marine unit operated. But barring these differences, I believe that a bad medic(corpsman), just like a bad grunt, would never have lasted in the bush for any length of time. If he wasn't dusted, he was transfered out if the CO had his shit together. Why did it take so long to get rid of this particular medic?<br><br>
Secondly, as a platoon medic, I have never seen any self inflicted wounds in my unit. I have seen many toss their daily anti-malarial pills hoping to get a couple of weeks out of the field, but, I have never seen or known of any to have caused such injuries to themselves. Frankly, I am offended and am trying not to personalize your characterization of those who were dusted from the bush. But, I would like to know where your information comes from on this issue, that &quot;many in &quot;Nam caused their own self inflicted wounds&quot;.<br><br>
I am sorry that you were saddled with a piss poor corpsman. You are right that all were better off without him. But, I have corresponded with many wazzamarines who have nothing but praise for the corpsmen they had. Some of these were conciencious objectors. Some of the highest decorated corpsmen/medics were C.O.'s. It is indeed sad that you had one that had the potential of causing more harm than good.<br><br>
By the way, you and I may have been in the same A.O and same ops as the one you are referring to.
